{"key":"processedPost-12942871","value":{"id":12942871,"first":12919531,"last":12986003,"when":1279936988,"utime":"07/24/10 05:03 AM","content":"No, you cut slits and holes all over the mini-greenhouse.&nbsp; Fresh air is the number one pinning trigger.&nbsp; Mushrooms fruit poorly or not at all in stale air.&nbsp; They also benefit from a day/night temperature differential, so don't try to maintain a constant temperature.&nbsp; <br /><br />The main pinning triggers are full colonization, low CO2 levels due to massive fresh air exchange and air movement, which causes evaporation of moisture from the substrate, bright high frequency light on a day/night schedule, temperature changes on a day/night schedule, and misting a few times daily to replace moisture lost by the fresh air exchange.&nbsp; <br /><br />For cakes, the shotgun terrarium takes care of everything but the light and temperature changes.&nbsp; You're supposed to re-use the perlite forever.&nbsp; I haven't bought perlite in many years.<br />RR","title":"Re: Building the ideal NON-Perlite terarium. I've got some questions!"}}